subSubSection.paragraph:
Hadronotellus
Kieffer, 1917: 341 (original description. Type: 
Hadronotellus pedester
Kieffer, by monotypy and original designation. Synonymized by 
Kieffer (1926)
); Muesebeck & Walkley, 1956: 357 (citation of type species); 
Szabo
, 1966: 421, 422 (description, key to Palearctic species known to the author, keyed); 
Hellen
, 1971: 5, 22 (description, keyed).

Head with coriaceous microsculpture throughout; mandibles usually bidentate with teeth large and roughly equal in size, sometimes tridentate with medial tooth the smallest; clypeus projecting, typically with pointed corners; ventral frons sometimes with weakly indicated facial striae; central keel present or absent; antennal scrobe convex to concave, without transverse rugae or striation, never delimited by carinae; female antenna with ten flagellomeres (nine in 

G. paradigma

) and four clavomeres (three in 

G. moczari

); mesoscutum and mesoscutellum with coriaceous microsculpture throughout, occasionally with longitudinal striation or microsculpture in the form of transverse waves; epomial carina absent or weakly developed; netrion absent; mesoscutal suprahumeral sulcus absent; mesoscutal humeral sulcus absent or indicated by a smooth furrow; mesoscutum without humeral pit (sensu 
Chen et al., 2020
); axillula obliquely striate; metapleuron with 1-3 setae in anterodorsal corner, sometimes with a single seta in dorsal metapleural area, otherwise glabrous; metapleuron undivided dorsoventrally by a change in sculpture or setation; hind tibia with one or two pairs of subgenual spines; foveae along anterior T1 roughly equal in size, ending in a sublateral carina followed by a lateral pit.
